  }), "Chinese Glazes"), ". \xA0Chapter 8, Iron in Chinese Glazes, covers iron in detail, while celadons are covered throughout the book.")), mdx("p", null, "There\u2019s a great range of colour in Chinese celadons. \xA0In traditional celadons, color is mostly the result of materials containing naturally-occurring iron being fired in a reduction atmosphere, with the color modified by the balance of other oxides in the glaze as well as the underlying clay body. \xA0Relatively small amounts of titania, manganese, copper and even cobalt can affect the color in significant ways. \xA0Ancient kilns like Yue, Hutian, Longquan, and Yaozhou became associated with certain colors and qualities of celadon, as the materials used at those kiln sites naturally contained particular blends of oxides. \xA0In Jingdezhen, celadon glazes seem to have evolved from fairly simple geographically specific material-based recipes (e.g. 10 parts glaze stone from Yaoli, 1 part glaze ash from Leping) to extremely refined and intentional recipes with similar base glazes\xA0that incorporate\xA0additional materials for their specific ability to modify color. \xA0This lead to glazes named not just for kiln sites but also specific colors and qualities:\xA0\xA0\xA0\u5929\u9752 \uFF08sky blue with a small < .2% addition of cobalt\uFF09\uFF0C\u8C46\u9752\uFF08\u201Dbean\u201D celadon pure green iron celadon\uFF09\uFF0C\u5F71\u9752\uFF08\u201Dshadow\u201D lake-green)\uFF0C\u7C89\u9752\uFF0C\u7389\u9752 (jade celadon)\uFF0C\u51AC\u9752 (winter green)\uFF0C\u9E2D\u86CB\u9752 (bright duck-egg green), just to name a few."), mdx("p", null, "But celadons in the Song dynasty were mostly restricted to local materials. \xA0Thus if your local clay and glaze stone contained only trace amounts of titania and low amounts of iron (such as in towns near Jingdezhen), then you could produce the famously pure blueish-green\xA0", mdx("em", {
